review_blob: 12oz bottle pours a clear orange with some very frothy white head. Nose has some dried citrus peel and pepper, a little beery with that sticky slightly stale thing, some orange. Flavor is better with orange and grass and mild pepper, lemon, grapefruit, soap. Dry finish. Crushable.
beer_name: Greenport Harbor Pith and Peel IPA

review_blob: 16oz can pours a murky dark orange with some lacing, white head. Nose is classic IPA with soap, citrus rind, grasses, orange, light pine, light herbs. Flavor is sweet with malt a touches of sweet orange/tropical fruit, then soap and herbs. Dry finish and scary drinkable for 7.4%. I guess this is a flagship.

12oz can from the brewery pours a dark garnet amber with some ringing white head. Looks pretty crazy with ruby edges. Nose is mild, some grain, red pears, some dried fruit, mild dark wheat. Flavor is better, sweet and malty, chewy grain, some caramel, some dried fruit - fig/raisin, yeast, some neutral wood. Dry finish. Not a world beater, but cool to see them try this stylem
beer_name: DC Brau / Port City Zehn von Zehn

review_blob: On tap at The Sovereign DC pours a hazy yellow with some fast fading had. Nose is very nice and very inviting, lemon, yogurt, some white grape, some white sangria, musty, funk it more earthy than medicinal. Flavor is lightly tart with lemon, white grapefruit and white grape, light neutral oak, straw, wood pulp. Acid level is spot on. Very well done from them.

On tap at The Sovereign DC pours a hazy orange with a ring of white head. Nose has lemon, acid, a little champagne vinegar, some sulfur too. Flavor is tart with both lemon juice and vinegar, straw, white grapefruit. Too much acid on the finish.

On tap at The Sovereign DC pours an amber brown with some white head. Nose is interesting, theres a bit of boozy sweetness that you expect from a tripel, but a graininess too, some cherry/berry, a little almond, some marzipan. Flavor has some more raisn/berry thing, booze, tropical fruit, chewy grains including rye, candy sugar. Full bodied finish. An interesting take.

50cl bottle at The Sovereign pours a murky, rusty red with zero head. Muddy and not very appealing to the eye. Nose is good though, plenty of cherries, both dried and fresh, light vinegar, some light pomegranate. Flavor is tart with cherries and pomegranate and vinegar, a touch of caramel malt smooths some rough edges. Full bodied, acetic finish.

10oz glass at The Sovereign DC. Pours a hazy gold with some tight, white head. Nose is inviting and pleasant, lemon zest, white pepper, straw, grass. More IPA than Belgian Ale. Flavor has a little bit of tropical fruit, lemon, dried white grapefruit zest, pepper, coriander, straw. Dry finish. Had one of these on a night when I had many sweet Belgians and this was a nice respite.

750ml bottle pours a neon blue with some pinky head. Nose is solid, the fruit is there in the rawest form but there is plenty of grass/straw, mild grist, some neutral oak, mild funk. Flavor follows right along, the berry in question is obviously black or blue, theres a medium level of tartness, some grape too, reminds a bit of Lambrusco, neutral oak/sawdust too, just a little biscuit. Finishes with a level of carbonation that is bordering on distracting, but otherwise dry and light tart. Successful.

32oz growler from the brewery pours an extremely murky, basically opaque, orange with some frothy, white head. Nose has citrus, orange, tangerine too, a lot of muddled marmalade, some mild tropical fruit too, a little green vanilla. Oats are quite obvious in the flavor, theres a sweetness and a little graininess that makes the oats evident. Flavor is solid though, mild candy, orange, tangerine, a little orange soda. Finishes a little creamy, sort of full bodied but pretty drinkable too.

32oz growler from the brewery pours a murky, deep brown with some fluffy white head. Not really black. Nose is standard, toast, some cracker, mild vegetal hop, some blood orange, vinous. Flavor is simpler, malt focused with cracker and toast, soap, mild herbs. Dry finish. Lacks some complexity.

Ubiquitous in Lima, 12oz bottles, pissy gold with some fading head. Nose is lesser than other developing world lagers, metal, lemon candies, stale bread. Flavor has more stale bread, straw, soggy biscuit. Finishes watery.

A few 12oz tulips at City Taphouse in DC. Pours a translucent yellow with some ringing, white head. Big nose, honey and spice mostly, a little straw and lemon lurking. Flavor is YUGE with honey sweetness, plenty of spice too with clove dominating, straw, lemon, light candy as well. Sticky finish. Drinks heavy.
beer_name: Port City Mead Barrel Aged Tidings

review_blob: Pours a hazy dark orange with some clumpy, white head. Nose has tangerine and orange, heavy malt and honey comb, wet corn. Flavor is sweet with malt and honey and corn, some soapy bitterness, some grass too. Full bodied and oily on the finish.

12oz pour at the brewery is a very hazy orange gold with some ringing, white head. Nose is very nice, juicy with tangerine and oranges, mango and guava too, some fruit sweetness, a little orange blossom. Flavor follows with big tangerine and orange notes, a little apricot too, flower pollen. Finishes a little creamy, a little sweet with some citrus bitterness. This is very nice.

32oz growler from the brewery pours a clear gold with some sudsy, lacing white head. Nose has some lemon, light pine, light soap. A little catty, which makes me think theres a nice dose of Amarillo here. Flavor has some light candy sweetness, lemon, soap, a little lime, vinous too. Dry finish, bitter. A standard IPA. I like the idea of a rotating concept IPA.

33cl bottle at Canas y Tapas in Lima pours a hazy neon yellow with some ringing white head. Nose has grist, candy, tropical fruit, some esters and spice. Flavor has some vanilla cake, candy, tropical fruit, spice, yeast, a little breakfast pastry. Finishes oily and full bodied but not abrasive and not boozy.

10oz pour at DBGB City Center DC pours a hazy orange with some tight, white head. Nose has some dusty couch, straw, grass, dried citrus peel, some saw dust. Flavor has grist and stale crackers, lemon, some dried orange rind, dried grasses, a little paper. Dry finish.

beer_brewer_name: Cervecera del sur del Peru (Backus & Johnston - SABMiller)
review_blob: 33cl bottle pours a clear dark gold/orange with some ringing, white head. Nose is a touch trashy, cheap orange juice, some esters, clove, banana, wheat chaff. Not overly pleasant. Flavor is chewy with straw and wheat, yeast, mild spice, some chewed bubblegum. Messy on the finish. Not real good.

12oz bottle at Barbarian Miraflores pours a hazy deep amber nearing black with some spitty, off white head. Nose has nougat, mild chocolate, mild cola, some anise, molasses, marzipan too, dried fruit, almost some Belgian yeast lurking. Flavor is sweet, this is more like a dubbel or a stout that fermented real hot, raisin, candy sugar, malt, marizpan. Finishes a touch boozy. A bit messy. Could have been a bad batch.

20cl pour at the Miraflores location, pours a ruddy, burnt orange with some cloudy white head. Nose has biscuit, malt, orange, mild soap. Flavor has more of the malt/apple thing red ales give you, some hop bitterness, soap, biscuit. Dry finish. Easy drinker. Good intro beer in this market.

12oz bottle at Barbarian Miraflores pours an opaque black with some creamy, off white head. Nose has bread crust, dried grass, some dried lemon peel. Nose doesnt say "black IPA". Flavor is fine, malt, some molasses, a little caramel, light orange, light pine, light soap. Almost like an ESB or brown ale with black food coloring.

10cl pour at Barbarian Miraflores, pours a clear copper amber with some ringing white head. Nose has plenty of corn and malt, whoa, soggy bread, some orange, some mild spice, a little yeast, but lots and lots of corn. Flavor has more IPA character, lemon and soap, but lots of malt and lots of corn, some yeast, some bread. Sweet finish. Dunno about this.

10cl pour at the Miraflores location, pours an oily black with some sudsy, creamy tan head. Nose is more straight forward imperial stout, malt, burnt toast, molasses, some chocolate, some marzipan, light booze, dried fruit. Flavor is actually really nice, the malt character is quite delicious, well nuanced with black pepper, almost a blueberry reduction kind of thing, molasses, licorice, malt, toast, cola. Big malt character. Finishes oily but not hot. Nice.

100cl pour at the Miraflores location pours a murky, oily black with some sudsy, brown head. A little leggy, like a scotch too. Big nose, booze and port at the outset, light paint, German chocolate cake, tiramisu, some dried fruit, molasses. Flavor has condensed cola, chocolate, more of that tiramisu/boozy/coffee thing, some liquid smoke, big port character without the astringent booze. Finishes full bodied, oily but I would have thought this would be far hotter. All in all, fairly well done.
beer_name: Barbarian / Del Valle Roble Coche Bomba

review_blob: On nitro at the Miraflores location. Pours a hazy, amber brown with plenty of creamy, slightly off white head. Nose has some dusty grist, some bread crust, mild yeast, fairly mild though. Flavor is sweet with malt, a little brown sugar, some yeasty bread, a little orange, a little cream soda. Creamy finish. Nitro may have hurt the nose a bit.

12oz goblet at the Parque Kennedy location pours a murky, deep brown with some ringing, cream colored head. Nose has molasses, malt, a little cola, a little coffee, a little raw chocolate. Flavor is solid, roasty but not bitter or overpowering, bread, turbinado sugar, molasses, a little coffee, a little cocoa powder. Medium bodied and dry in the finish. Very well done.

20cl at the Parque Kennedy location, pours a hazy gold with some sudsy, white head. Nice, approachable nose, lemon and orange blossoms, some unripened pear too, mild sweetness, some grass, flower pollen, a little lychee even. Flavor follows right along, solid fruit with lychees and pears and mild jack fruit, lemon and orange too, soap. Finishes dry and lightly creamy. A stand out in this market.

20cl pour at the Parque Kennedy draft house. Pours a clear gold with some lacing white head. Nose has lemon and herbs, soap, orange, dried grass. Flavor is malty, grassy, a touch metallic, some lemongrass, lemon, orange, some soda. Finishes a bit soapy and dry.

12oz bottle from Deli Sitter Haus in Lima pours a hazy, deep orange with some ringing, white head. Nose has orange peel and pith, soap, some herbs. Flavor is better, pithy and bitter, soap, herbs, grass, orange, grapefruit too. Finishes with a big dose of bitterness.

8oz pour at the brewery pours a murky deep brown nearing black with some off white head. Nose is true to style, malt and molasses, chewy grain, a little BBQ sauce, some earthy notes too. Flavor follows, bread, caramel, molasses, hints of vanilla and root beer, a little soil too. Dry finish. Exactly what it should be. Well done.

10oz goblet at the brewery pours a clear amber with some faint lacing white head. Nose is heavy on orange peel malt and soap, mild herbs, quite a bit of malt too. Flavor balanced malt and soap well, mild biscuit, orange, herbs, caramel. Bitter finish. Not bad but just off the mark.

10oz goblet at the brewery pours a hazy orange with some frothy white head. Nose has lemon, grass, straw, a little corn. Flavor is much better, white grape, preserved lemon rind, grass, straw, a little soap, a yeasty character too. Dry and crisp on the end. Pretty good.

On tap at the brewery pours a hazy orange with some lacing white head. Nose has plenty of estery notes, clove, banana, bubblegum, floral, some light tropical fruit, mild candy. Flavor is sweet with honey and bubblegum, some nice wheaty Flavor and texture too, spice, almost hints of coconut milk. Fisher lightly sweet with some spice. Not a great style, but this is well done.

12oz glass at 1874 Taproom pours a clear gold with some frothy, white head. Nose is fairly mild, some grist, some honey, floral too, mild spice, mild lemon, a pleasant orange zest. Flavor follows, orange zest, honey, grass, straw, light pepper, some lemon. Dry finish. Extremely drinkable.
beer_name: Oveja Negra / Beer Stache Fresh Hops

review_blob: Crazy 16oz pour at 1874 Taproom in Barranco. Opaque, thick looking dark orange brown with some lacing, off white head. This must be the end of the keg, looks like a milkshake. Nose has herbs and dried citrus rind, a touch stale, some orange, light malt. Flavor has dried grist, dried citrus peel, some soap, some herbs. Medium bodied, bitter finish. Perhaps a bit old, but everything else is in balance.

12oz bottle pours a clear gold with some clumpy white head. You get the nose from way back and you know it well, metal, lemon, cheap stale malt, trashy. Flavor follows right along, heavy fake lemon, metal, some root veg, a bit of a sour note to it. Spritzy finish. Trashy.

16oz pint at Nuevo Mundo at Parque Kennedy pours a murky orange with some creamy lacing white head. Nose has orange and parm rind, some soap, some herbs, potpurri. Flavor is heavy with soap and parmesean rind, yeasty too, heavy citrus rind, cheesy, grassy, a little couch. Finishes dry. Meh.

16oz pint at Nuevo Mundo at Parque Kennedy pours an extremely murky dark orange with some lightly lacing white head. Nose is odd, soap, some cheese, earthy, yeast, orange, hints of spice. Flavor is chewy with grains and straw, perfume, herbs, honey, mild lemon, a bit tannic with black tea. Finishes astringent and tannic. Very odd.

12oz bottle at Nuevo Mundo at Parque Kennedy pours a hazy gold with some ringing white head. Nose has booze, tropical fruit, very estery, clove, banana, cakey too. Flavor is better, sweet with bubblegum and vanilla cake, spice, tropical fruit. Booze is oily and coats the tongue. Full bodied. Solid but again, perhaps fermented a touch hot.

12oz pint at Nuevo Mundo at Parque Kennedy pours a very murky brick red with some creamy slightly off white head. Nose has apple sauce, orange, some under ripe pear, mild soap, a little caramel. Flavor is sweet with malt and caramel, chewy grain, soap, some blood orange, some mild spicy rye. Dry finish. Another beer that seems to be fermented a bit hot.

On draft at Nuevo Mundo at Parque Kennedy pours a very murky, nearly opaque orange with some lacing white head. End of the keg? Lots of haze. Nose is pithy, orange, lemon, a little cedar, soap, potpurri. Flavor is very bitter and pithy, orange rind, lemon rind, soap, grass, yeast. Full bodied, bitter finish. Almost an ESB the way the hops are used.

375ml bottle pours a murky peach gold with some white head. Nose has peach, BBQ sauce, nectarine, white grapes. Flavor has peach, nectarine, a little white grapefruit, white grapes. Medium bodied, tart and fruity finish.

12oz bottle pours a murky deep brown/black with some foamy, beige head. Nose is cool, chocolate, raw cinnamon, earthy, malt, cola, mild pepper. Flavor is sweet with malt and molasses, spice, anise, cinnamon, mild coffee, chocolate, pepper. Full bodied, creamy, spicy finish. A nice surprise.

375ml bottle pours a dark orange with some creamy, white head. Nose has grapefruit rind, some nettles, barrel, funk, preserved lemon. Flavor is tart with grapefruit and passionfruit, lemon, nettles, sour barrel. Medium bodied finish.

22oz bottle pours a murky, deep brown with some thick, beige head. Nose has malt, brown sugar, molasses, some vanilla, some booze. Flavor is hot with booze, vanilla, caramel, some cheap whiskey. Finishes hot.
beer_name: Clown Shoes Flight of the Angry Beast

review_blob: 22oz bottle pours a clear gold with some foamy, white head. Nose has corn, malt, sugar, some yeast. Flavor has bread, corn, malt, lemon, yeast. Full bodied finish. Yep, thats a 9% cream ale.
beer_name: Clown Shoes Moses and the Misfits

review_blob: 12oz bottle pours an oily brown/black with a ring of fading white head. Nose is big with booze and molasses, nougat too, vanilla, some wet wood, mild smoke. Flavor is a touch watery, molasses, malt, bread, vanilla, booze, caramel, mild smoke. Finished oily.
beer_name: De Molen Wal & Schip (Wild Turkey B.A.)

review_blob: 750ml bottle pours a bright purple with some cloudy, white head. Nose has cherry, some orange, some jam, mild berry. Flavor is tart with cherries, a very heavy orange bitters thing, berry flavored soda too, mild vinegar. Finishes a bit hot with acid.

12oz bottle pours a clear, brick red amber with some cloudy, white head. Nose has stale grist, paper, some wet dog, mild orange, caramel. Flavor has booze, candlewax, grist, bread crust, a little ketchup. Full bodied, boozy finish.
beer_name: Red Brick Beard Envy Barley Wine
